[The Michigan epidemic of hepatitis A has continued to expand while the parallel one in Southern California, primarily in San Diego county, seems to be abating. This is likely to be, in part, related to more spill over of infection into MSMs (men who have sex with men) and food handlers and, in part, due to less of a change in the paradigm of prevention as occurred in San Diego. Both outbreaks are being fueled by difficulties in sanitation rather than difficulties in identifying a food vehicle. The Michigan outbreak is further complicated by the water shut offs in Detroit. Political issues between the Republican statehouse and the primarily Democratic Detroit area are also confounding variables. The need for changing preventive paradigms for infectious diseases in the 21st century will, no doubt, occur time and time again in a world beset by climate change and politicians with anti-science agendas. - Mod.LL]

